Notebook two. Querying with select.

This notebook is about the read path. The select statement is how you ask a database for data, and almost every other query you will ever write is some elaboration on it. By the end of this notebook you should know the full shape of a select, how to choose what comes out, how distinct really works, how null behaves inside expressions, and the most important mental model in all of SQL: the logical order in which the engine actually executes the clauses you have written.

We pick up where notebook one left off. The customers and orders tables we created in DuckDB are still sitting in learn dot d-b, so we just reconnect with the SQL magic and start querying.

Section one. The shape of a select statement. Every select has the same skeleton. There are seven clauses, and only the first two are mandatory. Select, which lists what comes out. From, which says where the rows come from. Where, which filters rows. Group by, which collapses rows into groups. Having, which filters those groups. Order by, which sorts the result. And limit, which slices off the top portion. Each of those clauses has exactly one job, and the rest of the SQL series gives each one its own notebook. This notebook stays focused on select and from.

Section two. Choosing what comes out. The select clause is what relational people call a projection. It picks which columns and which expressions end up in the result. You can list five different kinds of things in a select. Existing columns, like name and email from customers. All columns at once with the star symbol, which is convenient in an ad-hoc query but a liability in saved code because anyone adding a column changes your output. Literal values, like the number one plus one, or the string hello, with no from needed at all. Expressions, which can be arithmetic, string concatenation, or date math. And function calls, like upper of name, length of name, or extract year from order date.

Aliases tie all of these together. You give an expression a result column name with the keyword as. The as is technically optional in most dialects, but writing it makes the intent obvious. Aliases matter because the engine has to label every output column, and a raw expression like amount times one point oh eight ends up with some auto-generated label that nobody enjoys reading. Give it a clean name like amount with tax, and the result becomes self-documenting.

Section three. Removing duplicates with distinct. The distinct keyword deduplicates the result. There are two things you need to internalize about it. First, distinct applies to the whole row of the projection, not to one column at a time. When you write select distinct column a, column b, you are asking for distinct pairs of column a and column b. You are not asking for distinct column a values separately from distinct column b values. Second, distinct is not free. The engine has to sort or hash every row to find duplicates. On a small table that cost is invisible. On a large table it is real, and you should ask whether you actually have duplicates in the first place, or whether what you really want is group by, which we cover in notebook five.

Section four. Null in expressions, and three-valued logic. Null does not mean zero. It does not mean the empty string. It means value unknown — the absence of a value. That single design choice has one large consequence. SQL uses three-valued logic. Every boolean expression evaluates to one of three values: true, false, or unknown. The moment null appears anywhere in an expression, the result becomes unknown.

Arithmetic with null gives null. Null plus one is null. String concatenation with null gives null, in standard SQL. Comparisons involving null give unknown. Null equals null is unknown, not true. Even negation propagates: not unknown is still unknown. The where clause treats unknown the same as false, so any row whose filter expression involves null silently disappears from your result. This is the single most common source of subtle SQL bugs.

Two functions handle null explicitly and you will use both of them constantly. Coalesce takes a list of arguments and returns the first one that is not null. It is your default-value pattern: coalesce of email comma the string no email on file gives you a sensible label for customers like Carol who have no email. Null if takes two arguments and returns null when they are equal, otherwise it returns the first argument. It is the inverse of coalesce, and it is useful for turning sentinel values, like the empty string or negative one, into proper nulls so the rest of your pipeline can handle them uniformly.

Section five. The logical clause order. This is the most important idea in the entire notebook, because it explains most of the surprises you will hit in SQL for years to come.

You write a query in one order: select, from, where, group by, having, order by, limit. But the engine executes those clauses in a different order. The execution order is: first from, to pick the source. Then where, to filter rows out. Then group by, to collapse the remaining rows into groups. Then having, to filter whole groups out. Then select, to project columns, compute expressions, and assign aliases. Then order by, to sort the result. And finally limit, to keep only the top portion.

Three consequences fall straight out of that order. First, the where clause cannot see select aliases. Where runs at step two. Select, where aliases are created, runs at step five. So when you alias length of name as name length in the select clause and then try to use name length in the where clause, the engine refuses, because at the moment where runs, that alias does not exist yet. Second, order by can see select aliases. Order by runs at step six, after select. That is why you can write order by name length without repeating the length of name expression. Third, you cannot filter aggregates in the where clause. Aggregates like sum and count only come into existence after group by runs at step three. A where clause that says sum of amount greater than one hundred is a category error: it is asking to filter a thing that does not exist yet. The right place to filter aggregates is having, which runs at step four, after group by has produced them.

We will exercise filtering and sorting properly in notebook three. The point of this section is purely the mental model. Once you carry the seven-step pipeline around in your head, you stop being surprised by which clauses can reference which names, and you stop reaching for where when having is what you actually want.

Section six. Pitfalls to carry forward into the rest of the series. Five of them. First, referencing a select alias inside a where clause. The alias does not exist yet at filter time. Either repeat the underlying expression, or wrap the query in a subquery or a common table expression — we cover those in notebook six. Second, expecting distinct to deduplicate per column. It deduplicates the whole projected row. If you want distinct values of one column regardless of the others, project only that one column. Third, using equals null instead of is null. The comparison evaluates to unknown, which the where clause treats as not true, so no rows come back. Always use is null and is not null for null checks. Fourth, leaning on select star in saved code. When columns change, downstream code breaks silently and without warning. Name the columns you actually need, and let the projection be the contract between you and your callers. Fifth, forgetting order by. The engine is free to return rows in any order it likes. If your test or your downstream code depends on a particular order, you must ask for it explicitly. Otherwise the test will pass today and fail tomorrow for reasons that have nothing to do with the code under test.

That closes notebook two. Next up is notebook three, filtering, sorting, and set operations, where the where clause, the order by clause, the limit clause, and the set operators union, intersect, and except all get the full treatment.
